Text: So it has been a fairly busy week for me this week.
On Wednesday was the deadline for COSC 326, so I had to spend a fair bit of time working on that.
Also my exam for COSC 343 was on Saturday so I also had to spend time studying for that.
Thankfully I was able to rely on my team at the start of the week to do preparations for our user testing.
Ruru was able to get all of the QR codes created and handed off to Yoko who was able to create and prepare handouts to give to the museum visitors to scan during testing.
Nene was also able to prepare a Google form survey to have the participants fill out to collect our data.
We had our usual Tuesday Zoom meeting with Mimi to show the web pages were live on Yoko's domain and get some feedback on a few small chances that he wanted implemented.
We also discussed with him our plans on our user testing for Wednesday which he seemed pleased with and had a couple of suggestions for us, and said he'd meet up with us during this time.
Luckily most of the changes that max wanted implemented were fairly minor and could be done in about 5 minutes.
Although one change he wanted was to make the audio player larger and more low-sight friendly.
This was much more difficult than I had thought it would be.
It didn't seem like you could change the default HTML one too much so I searched around for a JavaScript library and was able to find one that would fit the bill.

In our page we have the audio player included in the template above each image, and one problem I found with this particular player is that if you leave the audio source blank in the html that it would leave a loading icon on the audio player which might confuse the users.

I wanted to leave the audio player in the template so it would be easier for a non-IT person to implement but didn't want to confuse users, so I had to find a way to use JavaScript to hide any audio player without an audio source.
Which sounded easy at first but gave me a bit of trouble.
Luckily I was able to get this done before our user testing.
So on Wednesday we had our user testing which went really well.

We were able to meet with Mimi in person for the first time and he helped us get a stand to put a flier on with general information about the project and a QR code, which was placed by the door to the animal attic.
We were lucky to have some of the other Shift students join us and help our testing because it turned out on a Wednesday afternoon that not many people actually go through the animal attic.
We were lucky enough to get a few of the museum staff to have a go as well as a high school biology class on a field trip to help test for us.

Our findings were rather interesting in that the high school students immediately scanned the QR code on the stand by the door without being prompted, whereas most of the older visitors would walk right by it without looking at it.
We were interested to learn that the users would rather scroll through the web pages than scan the QR codes for individual items.
But overall we received very positive feedback and the museum staff were really excited about the project.
Also here is a team photo from our trip: .
The next days we spent wrapping up and preparing our final presentation, which we presented on Friday.
I think our presentation went well and we received some really good feedback again from Mimi who attended.
We still have some finishing up to do in terms of documentation for our hand over, which should be done early next week.

But with out project coming to it's conclusion there have definitely been a few things I've learned from this: It can be hard to keep track of what each team member is doing without proper processes in place, especially working remotely.
You can't always rely on the client to provide the resources required for the final prototype so it's easier to create a template to which they can add on.
I was able to learn how to use GitHub more effectively and manage merge conflicts.
Users may not always use your product how you expect them to.
